column5: How familiar are you now with ABCD Study experimental design, including participant sampling, recruitment, enrollment, and retention?

column11: How familiar are you with FAIR Data Principles and strategies for making research outputs follow these principles? (e.g., that data are Findable, Accessible, Interoperable and Re-Usable, how to make data FAIR via BIDS (Brain Imaging Data Structure) and NIDM (Neuroimaging Data Model) data structures, metadata, common data elements, terminologies/ontologies, and semantic annotation of data, pyNIDM - a Python library to manipulate the Neuroimaging Data Model.)
column12: How familiar are you with the computational basics? column13: How familiar are you with the neuroimaging workflows? column14: How familiar are you with statistics? (e.g., how to address the statistical aspects of reproducibility, the p-value and its limited ability to represent evidence in results, practical notions of power and associated tools, etc.")

column26: Applying all of the concepts we learned in a setting applicable to our interests! It's cool performing new techniques (like with containers, DataLad etc.) in a very general way with the weekly exercises, but actually utilizing it with data we're personally interested in was the best!
column27: Less meetings that check in on our progress because I had obligations outside of project week that I had to maneuver around. I think more responsibility pertaining to staying on track should be given to the groups themselves rather than having that mid-week check-in. I also think having an extra two or so days before project week to actually brainstorm the idea (before any actual implementation or data gathering) would be helpful because then actual project week can be strictly focusing on data cleaning/analysis.
column28: The TAs were the most helpful ever! I don't think we could have made it as far on our project without them. Project week help conceptualize everything together, like how containerizing fit in the grand scheme of analysis. While I can't say I'm officially comfortable with containers, I can at least report that I *know* what they are now. I'm also way better at dealing with Python script (I am an R user through and through). Lastly, I am a very introverted human who is not comfortable establishing new connections, but posting my project week idea and having others respond to it and help work on it was amazing! It brought me out of my shell a little more and opened up collaboration (especially collabs internationally!).

column26: My favorite thing was working with new collaborators, who are amazing, and seeing the initial stages of our project come to fruition in such a short period of time! The constant support and guidance of the ABCD-ReproNim TAs and Course Directors helped us to be able to figure complex things such as setting up an initial pipeline for connectome-based predictive modeling much more quickly than could have happened in outside of project week.
column27: I think it would be helpful to start project week off with some scheduled meetings between each project team and a ReproNim person to get people started right away with Datalad, containerization. Some of the conversations I had about containerization were helpful overviews, but it would have been more helpful to have them baby-step me through the process with a screenshare. We also got our Git workflow set up right away, but had deemphasized those things until later in the week. Wish we would have had done more ReproNim on day 1.
column28: I absolutely loved the ABCD-ReproNim course and project week. I think that everything we did was really helpful, especially having TA liaisons assigned to our specific projects who we could meet with ahead of time and throughout the week. I learned how to containerize environments (something i struggled to do previously!), got way better at python, learned calculated and visualized FC matrices for the first time, and produced CPM script from scratch! I could not have done it without the help of all of our team members; our team clicked immediately and we all left feeling like friends who will continue to stay in touch and collaborate to publish the projects we started. I also make great connections with some of the TAs who I plan to continue to feel comfortable to reach out to.

column26: The social learning aspect. Because everything is online right now, this is the most social learning I have had in over a year. It was excellent to know that not only was my team working together but everyone in the course was working together and helpful.
column27: Limit the amount of projects people can work on! Participants being able to be involved in multiple projects is great, but also puts a great limit on their own ability to contribute to each team they are in--even if that is not the intention.Another thing to improve is (if project week is online again) to not expect that each student can stop their lives for this hackathon-style week OR make very very clear expectations from the beginning. I knew I would need to dedicate a lot of time to the project week but I could not take off my other school/teaching/research responsibilities. I lessened the rest of my workload as much as I could but I could not dedicate my entire week to Project Week. I know in a "normal" hackathon week you would physically go somewhere and therefore need to take off most other responsibilities to focus on the task at hand. That isn't very possible for many students in this online world. It also ties into some of the privilege that some students have over others, they can take time off or tell their supervisors no, etc. (for future reference and planning) I can personally say that if the entire course was online and Project Week was in person, I don't think I would have applied for the course. I know I don't have the capacity or ability to leave my position for a week nor the travel funds.
column28: I found all ABCD-ReproNim course organizers, technical support, instructors, and teaching assistants useful during Project Week (and the entire course)! Everyone was very supportive and encouraging and it was a great environment to learn.I probably would have tried to prepare more for Project Week. Myself and my team met twice before the actual week itself but I still felt like I could've used more preparation for the big week. It's almost like I needed a structured Pre-Project Week as opposed to a freeform interim week. I felt prepared from the content given throughout the course but the ideas for Project Week themselves needed to be more formed.I did make new connections! It was great to see my little group everyday during our check ins.

column26: 1. the amount of support we get from TAs, instructors, and fellow participants (special thanks to Anna Vanucci and Morgan glover for sharing with me tips of how to organize the collaborative workflow efficiently!) 2. this atmosphere of putting aside other stuff to get things done (we really achieved a lot with our hard work!)
column27: the preparation week could have a more explicit instruction, for example, there could be a checklist of things that needs to be done before the project week, so we don't need to spare time to deal with them during the actual project week. This would help alleviate some of the pressure from the project leaders to think about how to organize this entire collaboration.For example: set up a group git repo and make sure to practice with branching and merging, if needed; set up a container that includes the basic softwares (they can modify it during the project week if needed, but after the initial step it would be much easier); upload the ABCD data that you'll need to the jupyter hubThese nitty gritty details take time, and some might be more difficult than expected, especially as group members don't have the same level of coding experiences.
column28: This is one of the most fruitful course experiences I've had in my grad school. I think the most beneficial experience is this hands-on project week, which really helps me achieve my data analysis goal. If not for this project week, I could imagine that it will take me more than 1 month to get to the same place.I also like its emphasis on open and reproducible science principles, and how it gets distilled into the coding practices. I don't have access to these discussions and training elsewhere, so it is really a game changer.

column28: I was lucky to find a fun and motivated team to engage with on the problem - a group I would not have met had it not been for the Project Week, especially in its virtual format (since I would not have been able to attend in person). I learned a lot from them in terms of neuroimaging as well as general approaches to a project and problem solving. The short and intense week was a very rewarding and exciting experience. This experience was enhanced so much more by the dedicated and highly approachable team of ABCD-Repronim organizers, TAs and instructors, who were very generous with their time to help us solve any problems we faced. This was the case not just with Project Week but with the entire course - I am in awe of the whole team that took on the humongous task of organizing and conducting this course, showing up and putting in the effort every week in spite of the  particularly challenging times we are going through.  Apart from significant knowledge of the ABCD study and the great lessons on reproducible science, the other important thing I will take away from this course is the inspiring example of the ABCD-Repronim team and what a dedicated and concerted team effort can accomplish in the worst of times.
